---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="Hello" description="Hello, there" current="hello">
  <article id="hello">
    <header>
      <h1>Hello</h1>

      <p class="subtitle">
        I tend to ask a lot of questions. Please don’t read anything negative
        into that. It is simply how I understand things.
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Questions are how I understand things.</li>
        <li>
          Clear answers are always welcome, including “no” or “I don’t know”.
        </li>
        <li>If something matters, please say it directly.</li>
        <li>Do not assume. Ask instead.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        When something is unclear to me, I ask. That is not meant to challenge
        you or slow things down. It is just how my brain builds a picture of
        what is going on.
      </p>

      <p>
        If I ask something, I would genuinely prefer an answer. “No”, “not now”,
        or “I don’t know” are all perfectly fine answers. Clear signals are
        easier to work with than silence.
      </p>

      <p>
        I also know that not everyone works this way. Some people prefer to
        process things internally and may not feel the need to ask questions out
        loud. That is completely fine.
      </p>

      <p>
        What usually works best is when different kinds of minds make their
        expectations visible to each other.
      </p>

      <p>
        So if there are situations where you would rather not answer questions,
        just tell me. I will happily respect that. What does not work very well
        is expecting me to somehow infer it.
      </p>

      <p>
        Most people go through life assuming that others think roughly the way
        they do. I have made the same mistake from the opposite direction,
        assuming people think the way I do. Both assumptions turn out to be
        unreliable.
      </p>

      <p>
        The rule I try to follow now is simple. Do not assume. Ask. And if
        something matters to you, say it clearly. None of us can read each
        other’s minds.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section aria-labelledby="tenets">
      <h2 id="tenets">Tenets</h2>

      <table>
        <caption>Core principles</caption>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th scope="col">Tenet</th>
            <th scope="col">Rationale</th>
            <th scope="col">Alternative</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Write things down and make them findable</th>
            <td>
              Knowledge should not depend on who you know, timing, or luck.
              Writing and publishing clearly reduces friction, lowers social
              barriers, and treats documentation as infrastructure rather than
              folklore.
            </td>
            <td>
              Or you could just... Reinvent the wheel every single time you do
              something
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Asking is a choice, not a requirement</th>
            <td>
              Conversation is valuable and often irreplaceable. But people
              should not have to interrupt, guess, or chase access to do their
              job or understand a system.
            </td>
            <td>
              Force people into behaving like you do, because if it feels right
              for you it must feel right for other people as well
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th scope="row">Publish where it can be found</th>
            <td>
              Writing is only half the work. Information should live in a place
              that is searchable, stable, and accessible to those who need it
              including future versions of ourselves.
            </td>
            <td>
              Keep the info to yourself, make people come to ask for it and you
              can feel important
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
